# Elegant tidyverse R (scoped paths)

Use this rule when editing R files matched by the globs above (`03_query_ai/`, `10_data_management/`, `**/fixer/**`). For tutorial-style scripts elsewhere, prefer [.cursor/rules/coding_style.mdc](coding_style.mdc).

## Style alignment

- Follow the [Tidyverse style guide](https://style.tidyverse.org/) (files, syntax, functions, pipes, ggplot2). Optional tooling: [styler](https://styler.r-lib.org/), [lintr](https://lintr.r-lib.org/).
- **Assignment:** always **`=`** for binding objects, never **`<-`**, per project [arrows.mdc](arrows.mdc) (same convention as [coding_style.mdc](coding_style.mdc)). This overrides typical tidyverse examples that use `<-`.
- Supplementary idioms: [Modern R Development Guide (gist)](https://gist.github.com/sj-io/3828d64d0969f2a0f05297e59e6c15ad) — not a substitute for the official guide; translate any gist snippets from `<-` to **`=`**.

## Package loading

- **Do not** default to `library(tidyverse)` — it attaches many namespaces. Call **`library()` only for packages this file uses**; use `pkg::fn()` for one-off calls when it avoids an attach.
- Quick map (see skill for detail): [Tidyverse packages](https://tidyverse.org/packages/) — core pieces include **dplyr**, **tidyr**, **readr**, **purrr**, **tibble**, **stringr**, **forcats**, **lubridate**, **ggplot2**. Add **httr2**, **jsonlite** for HTTP/JSON; **glue**, **reprex**, **tidymodels**, etc. only when needed.

## Pipe and modern dplyr (1.1+)

- Prefer **native pipe** `|>` (not `%>%`) for sequences of steps, per [Pipes](https://style.tidyverse.org/pipes.html) and the gist.
- Joins: prefer **`join_by()`** over legacy `by = c("a" = "b")` when it fits; use **`multiple`** / **`unmatched`** deliberately for join quality control.
- Grouping: prefer **`.by`** in **`mutate()`** / **`summarise()`** for per-operation grouping instead of `group_by() |> … |> ungroup()` when that is clearer.
- Use **`pick()`**, **`across()`**, **`reframe()`** where they simplify multi-column or multi-row summaries.

## Vectorized, data-frame–centric logic

- Center work on the **tibble/data frame**: **`mutate()`**, **`filter()`**, **`summarise()`**, joins — not row-at-a-time loops unless there is a real need (e.g. I/O side effects).
- Prefer **`dplyr::if_else()`** and **`dplyr::case_when()`** for column logic; prefer **`coalesce()`**, **`na_if()`**, **`tidyr::replace_na()`**, **`tidyr::fill()`** for missing-value patterns.
- Use **stringr** vectorized functions inside **`mutate()`**, not per-row loops for table logic.
- Scalar **`if` / `else`** is for **one-off control flow** (paths, config, interactive vs batch), not for recoding columns rowwise.
- Avoid `for (i in 1:nrow(df))` + `if` to build vectors; avoid **`sapply(seq_len(nrow(df)), …)`** emulating column logic.

## Programming with dplyr (rlang)

- Forward user column arguments with **`{{ var }}`** into data-masking verbs.
- Programmatic column names: **`.data[[var]]`** or **`all_of(vars)`** — not `parse()`/`eval()` or `get()` in data masks.

## purrr

- Prefer **`map(...) |> purrr::list_rbind()`** / **`list_cbind()`** over superseded **`map_dfr`** / **`map_dfc`**.
- Side effects: **`walk()`** / **`walk2()`**. For robust iteration over flaky operations, **`possibly()`** / **`safely()`** (often clearer than sprawling **`tryCatch`**).
- Prefer type-stable **`map_*`** over **`sapply`**.

## httr2

- Compose requests with **`request()`**, **`req_*`**, then **`req_perform()`** ([httr2](https://httr2.r-lib.org/), [Wrapping APIs](https://httr2.r-lib.org/articles/wrapping-apis.html)).
- Use **`req_error()`** for clearer HTTP failure behavior. For many requests, consider **`req_perform_iterative(..., on_error = ...)`**.
- Typed recovery (e.g. 404 → `NULL`): small **`rlang::try_fetch`** / targeted **`tryCatch`** on specific condition classes — not huge generic trees.

## Performance (one line)

- **Profile first** (**profvis**); compare alternatives with **bench::mark()** — keep readable dplyr until a hotspot is proven; see [Writing performant code with tidy tools](https://tidyverse.org/blog/2023/04/performant-packages/) and project skill **tidyverse-elegant-r**.

## Python in the same repo (lightweight)

- Prefer **pandas** (or **Polars**) chains / **`.assign()`** / **`groupby`** + **`transform`** over row-wise **`for`** + **`if`** forests when expressing the same table logic.

## Assignment (this repository)

- **Always** use **`=`** for assignment (including function definitions: `fn = function(...) { ... }`). Do **not** use **`<-`**. See [arrows.mdc](arrows.mdc).

